<li><a href="#Alternating-Dumbbell-Press">Alternating dumbbell press</a>.</li>



<li><a href="#Cable Lateral Raise">Cable lateral raise</a>.</li>



<li><a href="#Behind The Neck Press">Behind the neck press</a>.</li>



<li><a href="#Dumbbell-Arnold-Press">Dumbbell Arnold press</a>.</li>



<li><a href="#Barbell-Military-Press">Barbell military press</a>.</li>
</ul>
</div></div>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading list-start">Best Front Delt Exercises</h2>



<p>Here are the ten best exercises to isolate and target the front deltoid. Weâ€™ve included exercises done with dumbbells, a barbell, a weight plate, and cables to cover every training situation.</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="Dumbbell-Front-Raise">Dumbbell Front Raise</h3>



<p>The <a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/dumbbell-front-raise" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">dumbbell front raise</a> isolates the anterior, or front, deltoids. This exercise moves the front delts through their full range of motion. The secondary muscles that work are the clavicular head of the pectorals (chest), the serratus anterior, and the biceps brachii.</p>



<p>By using dumbbells, you can work each side of the front delts individually. This form of unilateral training prevents the stronger side from taking over, preventing uneven development. The dumbbell front raise is an isolation movement that requires slow, deliberate movement. During the movement&#8217;s lowering (eccentric) phase, you must resist gravity to keep tension on the working muscle.</p>



<p>The dumbbell front raise <a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/best-shoulder-workout-for-mass" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">builds muscle mass</a> and strength in the front part of the shoulder muscle. It also increases shoulder joint stability. This helps to improve sports performance when throwing and swinging a bat. Increasing shoulder stability also helps to reduce the risk of shoulder injury.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-block-embed-vimeo vimeo-custom wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">
<iframe title="Dumbbell Front Raises" src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/970294847?dnt=1&amp;app_id=122963" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; fullscreen; picture-in-picture; clipboard-write; encrypted-media"></iframe>
</div><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Dumbbell Front Raise Guide. Video: Aliaksandr Makatserchyk</figcaption></figure>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">How To Do&nbsp;</h4>



<ol>
<li>Stand tall with a pair of dumbbells held at your sides. Your palms should be facing toward your body.&nbsp;</li>



<li>Pivot from the right shoulder joint to bring your right arm directly up in front of you to chin height.</li>



<li>Slowly return to the start position, resisting the downward pull of gravity.</li>



<li>Repeat with the left arm.</li>



<li>Continue alternating sides to complete your rep count.</li>



<li>Breathe out as you lift the weight and in as you lower it.</li>
</ol>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Tips</h4>



<ul>
<li>Keep your shoulder blades pulled back.</li>



<li>Focus on contracting and squeezing the front delta as you lift and lower the weight.</li>



<li>Control the lowering (eccentric) as you resist gravity.</li>
</ul>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Optimal Sets And Reps</h4>



<figure class="wp-block-table table-default"><table><thead><tr><th>Training Style</th><th>Sets</th><th>Reps</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Strength Training</td><td>3</td><td>6â€“10</td></tr><tr><td>Hypertrophy</td><td>3</td><td>8â€“15</td></tr><tr><td>Endurance Training</td><td>3</td><td>12â€“30</td></tr><tr><td>Power Training</td><td>3</td><td>5â€“8 (Explosive)</td></tr></tbody></table><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Optimal Sets &amp; Reps of Dumbbell Front Raise</figcaption></figure>



<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-youtube wp-block-embed-youtube wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio youtube-custom"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">
<iframe title="ULTIMATE SHOULDER WORKOUT FOR MASS: Build Big Delts!" width="500" height="281" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/RtDE8HgKYU8?feature=oembed" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" referrerpolicy="strict-origin-when-cross-origin" allowfullscreen></iframe>
</div><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Best shoulder workout for mass. Video: WorkoutEndomondo</figcaption></figure>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="Barbell-Front-Raise">Barbell Front Raise</h3>



<p>The <a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/barbell-front-raise" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">barbell front raise</a> targets the front part of the shoulder muscle. The upper chest, serratus, latissimus dorsi, core, and biceps brachii support the movement. This exercise helps build strength and muscle mass in the anterior deltoid. It will also improve shoulder stability.</p>



<p>Strong front deltoids are essential for all pressing movements. So, performing the barbell front raise helps improve your strength on such exercises as the bench press and overhead press. It will also improve your functional strength for sports and everyday life when pushing against an opponent or lifting objects.</p>



<p>Using a barbell instead of a dumbbell requires a different form of stability through the core and serratus. This engages different secondary muscles. You may also be able to use slightly more weight with control when using a barbell.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-block-embed-vimeo wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio vimeo-custom"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">
<iframe title="Barbell Front Raises" src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/975306197?dnt=1&amp;app_id=122963" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; fullscreen; picture-in-picture; clipboard-write; encrypted-media"></iframe>
</div><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Barbell Front Raise Guide. Video: Aliaksandr Makatserchyk</figcaption></figure>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">How To Do&nbsp;</h4>



<ol>
<li>Stand with feet hip-width apart and a barbell held at armâ€™s length, with hands hip-width apart. In the start position, the bar should rest against your upper thighs.</li>



<li>Keeping your chest up and with a slight bend in your knees, bring the bar up to shoulder level. Do not bend the elbow so the only movement occurs in the shoulder joint.</li>



<li>Lower the bar to the start position, resisting gravity on the way down.</li>



<li>Breathe out as you raise the bar and in as you lower it.</li>
</ol>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Tips </h4>



<ul>
<li>Donâ€™t bring the bar higher than the shoulder level, as this may strain the shoulder joint.</li>



<li>Fight against the pull of gravity as you lower the bar.</li>



<li>Do not swing or otherwise use momentum in this exercise.</li>
</ul>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Optimal Sets And Reps</h4>



<figure class="wp-block-table table-default"><table><thead><tr><th>Training Style</th><th>Training Style</th><th>Reps</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Strength Training</td><td>3</td><td>6â€“10</td></tr><tr><td>Hypertrophy</td><td>3</td><td>8â€“15</td></tr><tr><td>Endurance Training</td><td>3</td><td>15â€“30</td></tr><tr><td>Power Training</td><td>3</td><td>5â€“8 (Explosive)</td></tr></tbody></table><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Optimal Sets &amp; Reps of Barbell Front Raise</figcaption></figure>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="Weight-Plate-Front-Raise">Weight Plate Front Raise</h3>



<p>The <a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/weight-plate-front-raise" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">weight plate front raise</a> uses a single weight plate to perform the front raise exercise. This makes it an excellent option for home trainers who do not have access to barbells, dumbbells, or cable machines.</p>



<p>This exercise targets the anterior deltoids primarily. The clavicular head of the pectorals, serratus anterior, and biceps brachii support the movement.&nbsp;</p>



<p>The weight plate front raise helps strengthen and develop the anterior deltoids. It also improves shoulder stability, helping to prevent injury and improve mobility. It also helps improve muscle definition and front shoulder mass.</p>



<p>This exercise mimics actions performed in daily life and sports. These include lifting objects overhead and pushing things away from the body, making it an effective functional exercise.&nbsp;The weight plate front raise works well as the second exercise in a <a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/shoulder-superset" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">shoulder superset</a>. Pair it with a shoulder pressing exercise.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-block-embed-vimeo wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio vimeo-custom"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">
<iframe loading="lazy" title="Weight Plate Front Raise" src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/980541038?dnt=1&amp;app_id=122963" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; fullscreen; picture-in-picture; clipboard-write; encrypted-media"></iframe>
</div><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Weight Plate Front Raise Guide. <span>Video: Aliaksandr Makatserchyk</span></figcaption></figure>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">How To Do&nbsp;</h4>



<ol>
<li>Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart and a weight plate held in front of your body. Grip the plate firmly on its edges.</li>



<li>Pivot from the shoulders to bring your arms up to shoulder level.</li>



<li>Slowly lower the weight, resisting the downward pull of gravity.</li>
</ol>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Tips</h4>



<ul>
<li>Maintain an upright torso and keep your shoulder blades pulled back.</li>



<li>Focus on contracting and squeezing the front delts throughout the movement.</li>



<li>Use a weight that allows you to control the eccentric (lowering) portion of the exercise.</li>
</ul>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Optimal Sets And Reps</h4>



<figure class="wp-block-table table-default"><table><thead><tr><th>Training Style</th><th>Sets</th><th>Reps</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Strength Training</td><td>3</td><td>6â€“10</td></tr><tr><td>Hypertrophy</td><td>3</td><td>8â€“15</td></tr><tr><td>Endurance Training</td><td>3</td><td>15â€“30</td></tr><tr><td>Power Training</td><td>3</td><td>5â€“8 (Explosive)</td></tr></tbody></table><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Optimal Sets &amp; Reps of Weight Plate Front Raise</figcaption></figure>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="Cable-Shoulder-Internal-Rotation">Cable Shoulder Internal Rotation</h3>



<p>The <a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/cable-shoulder-internal-rotation" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">cable shoulder internal rotation</a> is an isolation exercise for the rotator cuff muscles. It targets the subscapularis, which is one of the four rotator cuff muscles. The secondary muscles involved are the anterior deltoid, teres major, and pec major. These muscles stabilize and support the shoulder during the movement.</p>



<p>This exercise improves shoulder stability by strengthening the rotator cuff. This helps to improve mobility and reduce the range of injury when performing overhead movements. It is a popularly programmed exercise for rehabilitation following a shoulder injury.</p>



<p>Performing the cable shoulder internal rotation exercise helps ensure that the internal and external rotators are balanced in terms of strength. This reduces the risk of an imbalance-related injury.</p>



