<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="Cable-Lateral-Raise">Cable Lateral Raise</h3>



<p>The cable lateral raise is a popular shoulder exercise often performed by gymgoers and bodybuilders looking to develop well-rounded shoulders. It is sometimes completed after the <a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/dumbbell-front-raise" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">dumbbell front raise</a> which focuses on your anterior deltoids. The cable lateral raise involves shoulder adduction, which means you bring your arm away from the midline of your body.</p>



<p>Cable lateral raises work your <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537056/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">lateral deltoids</a> as the primary movers, They bring your arms away from the midline of your body as you lift the cable. Alongside this, your <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC10984646/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">anterior deltoids</a> and <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK531457/#:~:text=The%20serratus%20anterior%20is%20a,inferior%20angle%20of%20the%20scapula." target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">serratus anterior</a> muscles work as secondary movers. These muscles help to <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6849091/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">stabilize the shoulder joint</a> as you bring your arms out to the side.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Because of the constant tension provided, cable lateral raises are great for developing muscle strength and definition. They provide more <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8310485/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">time under tension</a> using a relatively easy movement pattern. Alongside this, they help to improve shoulder range of motion and stability when performed correctly.</p>



